Hi. You guys here for
the couples retreat?

14:46.768 --> 14:48.567
- Yeah.
- Really?

14:48.602 --> 14:50.472
See, I always figured two women together

14:50.473 --> 14:52.438
wouldn't have any trouble communicating.

14:52.473 --> 14:55.507
You guys must talk and share each
other's feelings all the time.

14:55.543 --> 14:57.943
Maybe that is the problem. (CHUCKLES)

14:57.978 --> 15:01.379
- (SPLASHING)
- Oh! Oh, oh. Okay.

15:09.889 --> 15:12.323
- (STEF GASPS)
- (JEANNIE GIGGLES)

15:14.661 --> 15:17.361
POPPY: Wait, so it's
doing that by itself?

15:17.396 --> 15:19.964
MARIANA: Yeah, the sensors are
bouncing sound waves off the walls

15:19.999 --> 15:21.276
so that's how it knows where to go.

15:21.300 --> 15:23.834
Hm, I can't believe
you know how to do this.

15:23.869 --> 15:26.319
Well, you build the robot
it's kind of just coding.

15:26.320 --> 15:27.838
It's really not that hard.

15:30.742 --> 15:32.108
EMMA: Shit!

15:33.712 --> 15:37.113
JESUS: Here, Emma, maybe you
could just adjust the sensors?

15:37.148 --> 15:40.115
Maybe I should have used an
ultrasonic instead of infrared?

15:40.150 --> 15:41.428
Okay, why don't you just change it?

15:41.452 --> 15:43.730
Yeah, but then our robots are
going to be exactly the same.

15:43.754 --> 15:45.688
There must be a problem with the code.

15:47.257 --> 15:48.524
Excuse me.

15:51.295 --> 15:53.128
Hey, you could help her, you know?

15:53.163 --> 15:55.342
I need this internship if I
want a chance to get into M.I.T.

15:55.366 --> 15:58.533
If I help her, I'm just
hurting my chances. So... sorry.

15:59.803 --> 16:01.636
Watch out for my robot.

16:03.807 --> 16:05.507
If you'll represent the Sinfuegos,

16:05.542 --> 16:09.210
we'll all write up the argument
and briefs as a class project.

16:09.245 --> 16:10.745
(SIGHS) (CHUCKLES)

16:10.780 --> 16:12.446
Look guys,

16:12.482 --> 16:15.516
I think the case Callie found
shows good legal precedence,

16:15.551 --> 16:18.752
but it's gonna be the Sinfuegos'
word against those ICE agents.

16:18.787 --> 16:20.683
And they are not going to admit

16:20.684 --> 16:22.823
they entered that home
under false pretenses.

16:22.858 --> 16:26.593
What if we could get an ICE agent
to testify on the Sinfuegos' behalf?

16:26.629 --> 16:27.861
Who witnessed the arrest?

16:27.897 --> 16:31.564
No, but he has knowledge
of these kinds of tactics,

16:31.599 --> 16:34.299
as well as other
inappropriate behavior by ICE.

16:34.335 --> 16:36.168
He's sort of like a whistle-blower.

16:37.438 --> 16:39.204
Maybe he could write an amicus brief?

16:39.240 --> 16:42.975
- CALLIE: What's that?
- It's like a person that's not directly involved with a case,

16:43.011 --> 16:45.811
but can educate or raise awareness

16:45.847 --> 16:48.079
about the issue with their expertise.

16:48.114 --> 16:50.949
That's well put, Amanda.
Look, I've gotta run but...

16:50.984 --> 16:54.553
if you can find that ICE
agent and get him to cooperate,

16:54.588 --> 16:56.120
I'll file the appeal.

16:57.891 --> 17:00.158
And I was serious about next year.

17:04.430 --> 17:08.933
I decided I want to apply
for the five year law program.

17:08.968 --> 17:11.068
You should, you're great at this.

17:12.538 --> 17:14.571
You get one chance to
say "I told you so."

17:14.607 --> 17:15.873
Oh, no. I wouldn't do that.

17:15.907 --> 17:18.407
Even though I did tell you so.

17:20.179 --> 17:22.111
So what about this ICE agent?

17:22.146 --> 17:23.846
Do you really think he'll testify?

17:23.882 --> 17:25.146
I don't know.

17:26.150 --> 17:27.784
I might need your help.

17:29.320 --> 17:32.455
Okay, this is an exercise in partnering.

17:32.490 --> 17:35.191
The objective is to row
your boat across the pond,

17:35.226 --> 17:37.026
working together as one

17:37.062 --> 17:39.294
without one party dominating.

17:39.329 --> 17:41.063
We can win this.

17:41.098 --> 17:42.931
BILL: Okay, on the whistle.

17:42.967 --> 17:44.265
(BLOWS WHISTLE)

17:44.301 --> 17:45.433
- Wow!
- Oh, okay.

17:45.469 --> 17:46.568
Push!

17:46.604 --> 17:48.670
Whoa, whoa! We...

17:48.706 --> 17:50.171
- (THUD)
- BOTH: Oh!

17:50.207 --> 17:52.340
- Okay.
- Okay, thanks for the push.

17:52.375 --> 17:53.887
- Yeah.
- STEF: Okay, we're going the wrong way.

17:53.911 --> 17:54.976
We're going the wrong way.

17:55.011 --> 17:56.477
- Row!
- No, no.

17:56.512 --> 17:58.412
- First, this way.
- Okay, ready and pull!

17:58.447 --> 18:00.681
- Row!
- No, you have to pull! Don't push!

18:00.717 --> 18:03.150
- I'm pulling.
- Stop! Oh, my god.

18:03.185 --> 18:05.230
Can you just let me do this
one first and then we can...

18:05.254 --> 18:07.855
But we're supposed to
pull at the same time.

18:07.890 --> 18:09.056
One, two, three!

18:09.092 --> 18:10.224
- (SPLASH)
- Hey!

18:10.259 --> 18:12.299
Okay, it is in the water
now. It's in the water now.

18:12.327 --> 18:13.627
Okay, if you... Okay.

18:13.662 --> 18:15.528
You're not supposed to dominate this.

18:15.563 --> 18:17.731
Who is dominating right now?

18:17.766 --> 18:19.532
(SIGHS) Can we... ?

18:19.567 --> 18:20.945
We're good! We're good, we're good.

18:20.969 --> 18:22.446
I got my... I got it,
I can put it right back.

18:22.470 --> 18:25.471
Ouch! That's my arm. That's my arm.

18:25.507 --> 18:27.674
STEF: Brad and Jeannie
are all the way to Canada.

18:27.709 --> 18:30.308
LENA: Well, Brad and
Jeannie can go to Canada.

18:30.344 --> 18:31.644
Well, it's a little difficult

18:31.679 --> 18:33.979
to row a boat with one
hand tied behind my back.

18:34.015 --> 18:36.448
- You were dominating.
- I don't... I was what? Dominating?

18:36.483 --> 18:38.583
What about that couple?
What about Brad and Jeannie?

18:38.619 --> 18:39.985
Turning it into a competition.

18:40.021 --> 18:42.375
What do you expect? This is a
retreat for straight couples.

18:42.380 --> 18:43.900
We have nothing in
common with these people.

18:43.924 --> 18:46.390
Exactly why I didn't want to
come here in the first place.

18:46.425 --> 18:48.425
See? I knew you couldn't
keep an open mind.

18:48.461 --> 18:49.794
Me?

18:49.829 --> 18:51.907
Why don't we just skip the
rest of it and go to the spa

18:51.931 --> 18:54.065
- or do whatever, you know? Shh, shh.
- Okay, h...

18:55.068 --> 18:56.167
Hello, there.

18:56.202 --> 18:57.368
STEF: Well, hello!

18:57.403 --> 18:58.469
BETH: How's it going?

18:58.504 --> 19:00.304
Just fantastic.

19:00.339 --> 19:01.472
Ready for group?

19:01.507 --> 19:03.840
More than anything. We wouldn't
miss it, would we, honey?

19:03.876 --> 19:05.508
Wonderful. Right this way.

19:06.812 --> 19:08.845
Hey, what... what's the point?

19:08.881 --> 19:10.291
- What?
- We don't have anything in common

19:10.315 --> 19:11.648
with these people anyway.

19:11.684 --> 19:14.818
Well, I think the point is that
maybe you should keep the open mind.

19:20.491 --> 19:21.740
They're good kids

19:22.230 --> 19:24.663
and we love them so much.

19:25.866 --> 19:28.166
But they take so much out of us.

19:28.202 --> 19:31.870
One has a learning disability
and that's been stressful.

19:31.905 --> 19:35.140
And, you know, teenagers...

19:35.175 --> 19:37.835
Uh, my wife had, I guess what you call

19:37.836 --> 19:40.200
an emotional affair with a coworker.

19:40.614 --> 19:44.415
And I guess that's made it
harder for me to trust her.

19:44.450 --> 19:48.019
I had a lot of unresolved
issues with my father.

19:48.054 --> 19:52.223
And I think it sometimes
gets in the way of my ability

19:52.258 --> 19:55.726
to be truly vulnerable and
intimate with my husband.

19:55.761 --> 19:58.496
BILL: Have you considered
confronting your father?

19:58.531 --> 20:01.297
I can't, he's dead.

20:01.333 --> 20:03.866
Is he?

20:03.902 --> 20:08.471
He's still a voice in your head, a
complication in your relationship.

20:08.507 --> 20:11.707
You know, he doesn't have to be here
for you to tell him how you feel.

20:13.912 --> 20:15.912
BETH: Would anyone else like to share?

20:17.548 --> 20:22.584
Uh, we have two kids leaving
for college... next year.

20:22.619 --> 20:26.988
And I guess what scares me is
what happens when they all leave?

20:27.991 --> 20:30.225
And it's just the two of us, again.

20:30.261 --> 20:35.196
You know, I mean we've been
co-parenting together so long,

20:35.231 --> 20:37.598
it's been the glue
that's kept us together.

20:39.569 --> 20:44.872
We can renew our vows all we
want, but if we can't connect,

20:44.907 --> 20:47.308
if we can't be vulnerable
with each other...

20:48.311 --> 20:51.744
(SIGHS) I mean, without the kids...

20:53.549 --> 20:55.582
will there by anything left between us?

21:02.023 --> 21:03.890
GRACE: You know, I'm
really proud of you.

21:03.925 --> 21:05.592
BRANDON: (CHUCKLES) For what?

21:07.661 --> 21:09.761
Applying to college and just...

21:11.699 --> 21:14.066
taking care of yourself.

21:15.069 --> 21:16.502
You sound like my mom.

21:16.537 --> 21:17.970
I do?

21:18.005 --> 21:19.705
Yeah, she...

21:20.941 --> 21:24.009
She thinks I'm like
a caretaker, you know?

21:24.044 --> 21:27.112
But I... I... I can
still be in a relationship

21:27.147 --> 21:29.214
and do what I need to
do for me, you know?

21:29.249 --> 21:32.650
So everyone can just stop worrying.

21:39.058 --> 21:40.825
God, it's so beautiful.

21:42.161 --> 21:43.594
Yeah.

21:45.864 --> 21:47.797
I'm more of a sunrise guy.

21:48.800 --> 21:50.200
Really? Why?

21:54.039 --> 21:57.107
I like beginnings.

21:57.143 --> 22:01.511
I don't know. Sunsets
are kind of like the end.

22:04.782 --> 22:07.816
Well, some things last forever.

22:10.188 --> 22:11.654
Like a selfie.

22:11.689 --> 22:12.921
(LAUGHS)

22:12.957 --> 22:14.357
Come on.

22:14.392 --> 22:15.723
- Please?
- All right.

22:19.530 --> 22:22.197
<i>♪ In the sunlight ♪</i>

22:22.232 --> 22:24.712
- (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING) <i>
- ♪ Your eyes are flashing brown ♪</i>

22:25.302 --> 22:26.535
(SHUDDERS)

22:26.570 --> 22:27.902
You cold?

22:27.937 --> 22:29.837
Uh, just a little chilly.

22:29.873 --> 22:31.406
I'll get you a sweater.

22:31.441 --> 22:32.873
Okay, thanks.

22:32.908 --> 22:37.645
<i>♪ You feel like an ocean and
I would surely love to drown ♪</i>

22:44.746 --> 22:47.100
__

22:49.957 --> 22:53.426
<i>♪ My eyes, rarely stay focused</i> ♪

22:53.461 --> 22:56.796
<i>♪ In one place for very long ♪</i>

22:56.831 --> 23:03.236
<i>♪ But I catch my gaze lingering
for more than just one song ♪</i>

23:03.271 --> 23:09.040
<i>♪ This I promise early, I
will never do you wrong ♪</i>

23:09.076 --> 23:13.144
<i>- ♪ 'Cause I can never wander too far ♪</i>
- Thank you.

23:14.415 --> 23:19.384
So, uh... why do you...
why'd you bring this?

23:19.420 --> 23:21.119
Uh, it's a good luck charm.

23:21.154 --> 23:22.454
For our gig.

23:22.489 --> 23:27.991
<i>♪ I'm extremely fond of you ♪</i>

23:43.642 --> 23:45.857
I know the agents who
arrested the Sinfuegos,

23:45.863 --> 23:48.530
I'm not surprised to hear they
used deception to enter the house.

23:48.566 --> 23:49.966
There's a lot of that going on.

23:50.001 --> 23:52.668
I need you to tell the
immigration judge that.

23:52.703 --> 23:54.903
And the other misconduct
you've told me about.

23:54.939 --> 23:56.072
No way.

23:56.107 --> 23:58.607
You can write it in something
called an amicus brief.

23:58.642 --> 24:01.676
We'll file it "under seal", the judge
won't have to share it with anyone.

24:01.711 --> 24:02.944
It'll get out.

24:02.980 --> 24:04.446
That type of thing always does.

24:04.481 --> 24:06.514
Look, I'm sorry but I can't help.

24:06.549 --> 24:08.783
We're going to compel you to testify.

24:08.818 --> 24:10.251
And how do you plan on doing that?

24:10.287 --> 24:11.652
(CAR DOOR OPENS)

24:11.688 --> 24:14.022
Who's this?

24:14.057 --> 24:16.958
CALLIE: It's my friend you helped
after he was arrested at the raid.

24:20.796 --> 24:22.229
What's this?

24:22.264 --> 24:23.663
A subpoena.

24:26.102 --> 24:29.103
Sorry. You've been served.

24:46.721 --> 24:49.822
Our very first motel room together.

24:49.857 --> 24:55.494
It's not the Golden Door
Spa, but... it has a bed.

24:56.863 --> 24:58.397
That's all that matters, right?

24:58.432 --> 24:59.432
Mm-hmm.

25:03.770 --> 25:04.969
♪ ♪

25:09.509 --> 25:10.747
STEF: Well, the food was a lot better

25:10.748 --> 25:12.589
than I thought it'd
be, didn't you think?

25:14.247 --> 25:15.446
What's that?

25:15.481 --> 25:17.981
It's my assignment.

25:18.017 --> 25:21.852
Supposed to write an x-rated
letter to "my husband"

25:21.887 --> 25:23.954
about all of our past sex-capades,

25:23.989 --> 25:26.089
but I went a little more romantic.

25:26.124 --> 25:29.926
(LAUGHS) Come on, are we really gonna
do this whole his and hers thing?

25:32.597 --> 25:33.963
Forget it.

25:33.998 --> 25:35.598
Well... (SIGHS)

25:35.633 --> 25:38.701
Lena, I have said yes to
everything today. I have.

25:38.736 --> 25:40.103
Everything except me.

25:40.138 --> 25:42.237
- Oh, come on.
- What? You went through the motions,

25:42.273 --> 25:43.838
but we never connected.

25:43.874 --> 25:46.308
You never said a word in group.

25:46.343 --> 25:48.522
What am I supposed to say
after you basically questioned

25:48.546 --> 25:50.490
whether or not we'd stay together
after the kids leave home?

25:50.514 --> 25:52.392
Well, let's talk about
that. Let's talk about that

25:52.416 --> 25:54.528
and everything else that's
been going on instead of just...

25:54.552 --> 25:56.751
paddling around in a circle
and never getting anywhere.

25:56.787 --> 25:59.065
I mean, talk about the perfect
metaphor for our relationship.

25:59.089 --> 26:01.655
If you are so afraid of us not
staying together, then tell me!

26:01.691 --> 26:04.092
Not a whole group of
strangers, for God's sake.

26:04.127 --> 26:06.294
I'm telling you. I
have been telling you.

26:07.297 --> 26:09.863
All you tell me is
that you're not happy.

26:09.899 --> 26:11.201
And it's not because of Tess,

26:11.202 --> 26:13.267
but it's because of
how you feel about Tess.

26:13.303 --> 26:16.103
I mean... talk about
an emotional affair.

26:16.138 --> 26:18.138
Is that what's going on?
Is that what's happening?

26:18.173 --> 26:20.006
No, Lena, that would be your M.O.

26:21.843 --> 26:23.477
So... so you still resent me for that?

26:23.512 --> 26:24.844
You don't trust me?

26:24.879 --> 26:26.179
I don't trust anyone.

26:29.118 --> 26:31.451
I'm gonna go get some air.

26:44.732 --> 26:46.532
I love you.

26:46.567 --> 26:48.033
I love you.

26:49.270 --> 26:54.272
<i>♪ Am I a fool? ♪</i>

26:54.307 --> 26:56.922
I don't know why I didn't
just get back with Aaron

26:56.923 --> 26:58.042
when I had the chance.

26:59.346 --> 27:01.446
I mean, it's not too late, right?

27:01.481 --> 27:03.515
He said he's taking it
slow with that girl, Amanda.

27:03.550 --> 27:06.717
Yeah, overnight bag slow.

27:08.787 --> 27:12.456
The other night it was
obvious she was staying over.

27:16.162 --> 27:21.198
I just don't want to be that girl
who stabs another girl in the back.

27:21.233 --> 27:25.067
This world pits women against
each other too much as it is.

27:28.105 --> 27:29.472
Yeah, but...

27:30.675 --> 27:32.975
No girl wants to be
a guy's second choice.

27:33.010 --> 27:36.612
And... I mean, it's not like
you're trying to get him into bed.

27:36.648 --> 27:40.183
You're just telling him how you feel
and I think he needs to know that.

27:41.985 --> 27:44.252
Look, Callie,

27:44.288 --> 27:46.954
you don't have to keep creating
these tragic love stories.

27:48.058 --> 27:49.591
Just say yes.

27:57.067 --> 28:00.334
(GOAT BLEATS)

28:05.874 --> 28:07.608
Hey, little guy.

28:08.911 --> 28:10.944
What are you doing out
here all by yourself?

28:13.349 --> 28:14.848
There you go.

28:16.751 --> 28:18.384
Back with your buds.

28:18.420 --> 28:21.688
That's it, safe and sound.

28:23.425 --> 28:26.092
FRANK: I used to love the
goats on my grandfather's farm.

28:29.063 --> 28:30.330
I didn't know he had goats.

28:30.365 --> 28:31.931
And chickens.

28:31.966 --> 28:36.635
And a llama. God knows why.
Anyway, they were great summers.

28:37.938 --> 28:39.438
I wish I'd met your grandfather.

28:39.473 --> 28:41.506
He was an asshole.

28:41.542 --> 28:44.909
I liked the farm and the
animals, but him? Not so much.

28:47.080 --> 28:48.647
What are you doing here, Dad?

28:48.682 --> 28:50.814
You said something to Brandon about

28:50.850 --> 28:54.352
the messages you receive
in childhood stay with you?

28:54.387 --> 28:57.020
Well, I'm the messenger. Right?

28:57.056 --> 28:59.189
I mean, I ruined you.

29:01.961 --> 29:03.127
Whatever.

29:05.030 --> 29:06.363
(GOAT BLEATS)

29:09.568 --> 29:12.508
You can't keep walking away from people

29:12.509 --> 29:13.836
unless you want to end up alone.

29:15.940 --> 29:20.176
At some time you gotta
plant your feet, have it out.

29:20.211 --> 29:21.378
So...

29:22.748 --> 29:26.214
what was it that you wanted
that I didn't give to you?

29:26.250 --> 29:27.516
Let me hear it.

29:27.551 --> 29:28.917
What?

29:31.822 --> 29:34.323
What every kid wants,
Dad. Your approval.

29:36.427 --> 29:37.660
(SIGHS)

29:37.695 --> 29:40.395
That's why I became a cop.
That's why I married Mike.

29:40.430 --> 29:42.430
That's why I tried to be straight.

29:42.465 --> 29:43.731
Hm.

29:43.767 --> 29:45.800
How'd that work out for you?

29:47.370 --> 29:50.505
Not great, your...

29:50.540 --> 29:55.142
rejection of me and my sexuality
made me feel ashamed of myself

29:55.178 --> 29:57.544
and I still feel ashamed of myself.

29:59.615 --> 30:01.448
I'm not here anymore.

30:04.019 --> 30:05.519
You're not gone.

30:09.124 --> 30:10.924
What do you want me to say?

30:16.698 --> 30:18.964
That you're sorry. That...

30:21.436 --> 30:23.769
That you love me, that
you're proud of me,

30:23.805 --> 30:26.439
of who I am, of who I love

30:26.474 --> 30:28.641
and my beautiful children.

30:31.345 --> 30:33.745
That there's nothing wrong with me.

30:40.987 --> 30:43.187
I can't say all that.

30:47.260 --> 30:49.626
(CRYING) I know, I know.

30:51.196 --> 30:52.629
But you can say it...

30:52.665 --> 30:53.964
to yourself.

30:56.001 --> 30:57.100
Say it.

31:04.510 --> 31:07.643
I love me. I love me.

31:07.679 --> 31:09.278
I love...

31:11.315 --> 31:13.783
who I am, I'm proud of me...

31:17.054 --> 31:20.222
and who I love, my beautiful Lena.

31:22.959 --> 31:24.993
And my beautiful kids,

31:25.028 --> 31:26.728
and this...

31:27.865 --> 31:30.098
this life we have made.

31:36.139 --> 31:38.172
And there's nothing wrong with me.

31:39.909 --> 31:43.411
When you can truly believe that...

31:46.348 --> 31:50.183
maybe then... that all the...

31:52.955 --> 31:57.557
the shitty things that I said or did,

31:57.592 --> 31:59.659
they wouldn't matter so much.

32:00.662 --> 32:02.228
And that maybe...

32:03.732 --> 32:05.665
you'd remember all
the things I did right.

32:07.001 --> 32:08.668
Like love you.

32:08.703 --> 32:10.303
Which I did.

32:11.840 --> 32:13.139
And always will.

32:49.637 --> 32:51.369
(DOOR CLOSES)

33:02.982 --> 33:05.215
When Tess moved in next door,

33:05.251 --> 33:07.952
um, it...

